  "prompt": "How do I save an answer on Quora?",
  "response": "There are a couple of ways to save answers on Quora, depending on what you mean by \"save\":\n\n**1. Saving an Answer to Read Later (Bookmarks/Reading List):**\n\nThis is the most common meaning of \"saving an answer.\" You want to bookmark it so you can easily find it and read it later.\n\n*   **How to do it:**\n    1.  **Look for the three dots (...)** at the bottom right corner of the answer you want to save.\n    2.  **Click the three dots (...).**\n    3.  **Select \"Save answer\".**\n\n*   **Where to find your saved answers:**\n    1.  On the left sidebar (on the web version) or the bottom navigation bar (on the mobile app), look for **\"Following\"**.\n    2.  Click on **\"Following\"**.\n    3.  You should see a tab called **\"Saved\".** Click on it.\n    4.  All your saved answers will be listed there.  You can also organize them into lists from this page.\n\n**2. Saving Your Own Answer (So you don't lose it before posting):**\n\nIf you're worried about losing a long answer you're writing, Quora usually auto-saves drafts as you type.\n\n*   **Drafts:** When you are writing an answer, Quora automatically saves your progress. If you navigate away from the question before posting, a draft will be saved. You can usually find the draft by going back to the question page, or by going to your profile and then \"Drafts\".\n*   **Copy and Paste:** As a precaution, especially for very important answers, you can copy and paste your answer into a separate document (like a text editor or word processor) on your computer. This way, you have a backup regardless of what happens on Quora.\n\n**In summary:**\n\n*   **To save *someone else's* answer for later reading: Use the \"Save answer\" option under the three dots.**\n*   **To protect *your own* answer while you're writing it: Rely on Quora's auto-save drafts feature, and consider copying and pasting into a separate document for extra safety.**\n",
